<trans-unit id="ffba6dd5-d68b-47af-9ef5-a1d1cdea7be8"><source>Action on HFCs: increasingly important to addressing climate change</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="6">Action on HFCs: increasingly important to addressing climate change</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="6" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="9f505938-dfd5-49f1-89fd-e2f642c539f5"><source>HFCs (hydrofluorocarbons) are potent greenhouse gases.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="7">HFCs (hydrofluorocarbons) are potent greenhouse gases.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="7" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="9f139893-85d1-466b-85c5-7846f63bdb76"><source>The most commonly used HFCs have global warming potentials (GWP) 1000x that of C0<g id="pt7">2</g>, and many HFCs are also short-lived climate pollutants.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="8">The most commonly used HFCs have global warming potentials (GWP) 1000x that of C0<g id="pt7">2</g>, and many HFCs are also short-lived climate pollutants.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="8" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="f3f8a608-7ad6-4bd4-a4a6-c8a71961d894"><source>HFCs were developed to replace CFCs and HCFCs, ozone depleting substances (ODS) being phased-out under the Montreal Protocol.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="9">HFCs were developed to replace CFCs and HCFCs, ozone depleting substances (ODS) being phased-out under the Montreal Protocol.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="9" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="b23cd088-9c74-41dc-a56f-e172245ae8e9"><source>They are mostly used in the refrigeration, air conditioning and insulation foam sectors.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="10">They are mostly used in the refrigeration, air conditioning and insulation foam sectors.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="10" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="189b78c1-a643-4cf7-a3e0-6c317793d675"><source>While HFCs currently comprise <g id="pt8">1-2% </g>of global CO<g id="pt9">2</g> equivalent (CO<g id="pt10">2</g>e) emissions, emissions are rising by <g id="pt11">9% per year </g>as HCFC phase-out progresses.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="11">While HFCs currently comprise <g id="pt8">1-2% </g>of global CO<g id="pt9">2</g> equivalent (CO<g id="pt10">2</g>e) emissions, emissions are rising by <g id="pt11">9% per year </g>as HCFC phase-out progresses.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="11" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="f98969d4-7942-4b64-8106-1126c79782b8"><source>According to various emission projection scenarios, HFCs could comprise as much as <g id="pt12">7-19%</g> of global CO<g id="pt13">2</g>e emissions by 2050.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="12">According to various emission projection scenarios, HFCs could comprise as much as <g id="pt12">7-19%</g> of global CO<g id="pt13">2</g>e emissions by 2050.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="12" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="32d51c3b-f05c-415a-ba26-cfa4e900a434"><source>Addressing HFCs has the potential to deliver high GHG abatement in a cost effective way due to their high GWPs, concentration in a few sectors, and the fact that lower GWP substitutes are becoming available for some uses, e.g. mobile air conditioning systems.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="13">Addressing HFCs has the potential to deliver high GHG abatement in a cost effective way due to their high GWPs, concentration in a few sectors, and the fact that lower GWP substitutes are becoming available for some uses, e.g. mobile air conditioning systems.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="13" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="e9e51111-dec0-4588-8bdd-1915a6c676b1"><source>Without <g id="pt16">controls, HFC emissions are expected to grow </g>significantly</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="14">Without <g id="pt16">controls, HFC emissions are expected to grow </g>significantly</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="14" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
