<trans-unit id="f95fa0f7-e3cf-4ee5-8cab-ebaec55aff5c"><source>Canada is already addressing HFCs through a variety of domestic and international initiatives:</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="23">Canada is already addressing HFCs through a variety of domestic and international initiatives:</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="23" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="00194677-2bdf-4cfc-8560-d587835bd934"><source><g id="pt38">International</g>: Proposals under the Montreal Protocol as well as the Climate and Clean Air Coalition (CCAC).</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="24"><g id="pt38">International</g>: Proposals under the Montreal Protocol as well as the Climate and Clean Air Coalition (CCAC).</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="24" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="1b57fbd8-4f95-4369-9bf0-82cd96afdb87"><source><g id="pt39">Domestic</g>: Some HFC emissions are subject to limited controls under provincial and federal regulations; there are plans to improve data on HFC uses and imports; HFCs included in strategy on short-lived climate pollutants under development.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="25"><g id="pt39">Domestic</g>: Some HFC emissions are subject to limited controls under provincial and federal regulations; there are plans to improve data on HFC uses and imports; HFCs included in strategy on short-lived climate pollutants under development.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="25" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="df07f2b0-6bd0-484f-83f7-d964039f0d94"><source>These activities are aligned with Canada’s climate change and other environmental priorities, and have allowed us to:</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="26">These activities are aligned with Canada’s climate change and other environmental priorities, and have allowed us to:</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="26" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="00881952-235f-4335-8a76-23c854a6a55d"><source>Demonstrate leadership on short-lived climate pollutants;</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="27">Demonstrate leadership on short-lived climate pollutants;</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="27" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="4da2b56b-dec4-4f9a-8d1d-97291bb58e3f"><source>Pursue a harmonized approach with the U.S. and Mexico; and</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="28">Pursue a harmonized approach with the U.S. and Mexico; and</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="28" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="07029436-5797-4f8b-a173-6546d4ed3177"><source>Gain international recognition of efforts to address climate change.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="29">Gain international recognition of efforts to address climate change.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="29" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="5656aef5-4a7a-4eee-b855-ebf9a65fc5b0"><source>The Montreal Protocol</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="30">The Montreal Protocol</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="30" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="9d2ecfc5-fb8c-4293-8117-517d6768d93d"><source>Every year since 2009, Canada, the US and Mexico have submitted a joint proposal to phase-down HFC consumption and production under the Montreal Protocol.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="31">Every year since 2009, Canada, the US and Mexico have submitted a joint proposal to phase-down HFC consumption and production under the Montreal Protocol.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="31" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="55f6109a-29c5-4911-9205-74e36f404b03"><source><g id="pt44">Although </g><g id="pt45">HFCs are </g><g id="pt46">a type of gas covered </g><g id="pt47">under the UNFCCC, </g><g id="pt48">the Convention does not currently offer a way to control specific gases.</g></source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="32"><g id="pt44">Although </g><g id="pt45">HFCs are </g><g id="pt46">a type of gas covered </g><g id="pt47">under the UNFCCC, </g><g id="pt48">the Convention does not currently offer a way to control specific gases.</g></mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="32" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="cee54796-4585-46f1-8835-580c74142f24"><source>The North American Proposal to address HFCs under the Montreal Protocol is a more effective approach because:</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="33">The North American Proposal to address HFCs under the Montreal Protocol is a more effective approach because:</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="33" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="02fee341-1fa2-444b-ba8e-3d490925dea7"><source>The phase out of ODS under the Montreal Protocol is indirectly driving the global increase in HFC emissions, and HFCs are used in the same sectors as ODS;</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="34">The phase out of ODS under the Montreal Protocol is indirectly driving the global increase in HFC emissions, and HFCs are used in the same sectors as ODS;</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="34" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="f8048d25-a0c7-409b-805d-318d37b5ef88"><source>The Montreal Protocol has the appropriate control regime, expertise, and financial mechanism to do the work based on its successful track record in phasing-down other gases; and</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="35">The Montreal Protocol has the appropriate control regime, expertise, and financial mechanism to do the work based on its successful track record in phasing-down other gases; and</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="35" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="cf6901c2-4138-43b0-aa3c-655f24e2f7a1"><source>A phase-down under the Montreal Protocol would allow for the mandatory reduction of HFC emissions within both developed and developing countries (something that is not possible under the current UNFCCC structure).</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="36">A phase-down under the Montreal Protocol would allow for the mandatory reduction of HFC emissions within both developed and developing countries (something that is not possible under the current UNFCCC structure).</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="36" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="9af1954b-5bac-4e8e-acab-58907bad1f49"><source>Climate and Clean Air Coalition</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="37">Climate and Clean Air Coalition</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="37" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="a11cd2fa-b806-48d9-9cb4-cf94cfaf912d"><source>Canada is a founding member of the Climate and Clean Air Coalition (CCAC) to reduce short-lived climate pollutants (SLCPs).</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="38">Canada is a founding member of the Climate and Clean Air Coalition (CCAC) to reduce short-lived climate pollutants (SLCPs).</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="38" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="25fe1b25-230e-428d-b9d3-a661a930aa76"><source>This initiative was launched in February 2012 to generate fast action on a range of SLCPs including methane, black carbon and HFCs.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="39">This initiative was launched in February 2012 to generate fast action on a range of SLCPs including methane, black carbon and HFCs.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="39" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="cacb58f1-2d39-4870-9c4e-6010211adfca"><source>The Coalition has agreed to address HFCs by fast-tracking more environmentally-friendly and cost effective HFC alternatives and technologies to avoid HFC growth.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="40">The Coalition has agreed to address HFCs by fast-tracking more environmentally-friendly and cost effective HFC alternatives and technologies to avoid HFC growth.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="40" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="28c7189f-1eab-41aa-8d42-4ec092ad240b"><source>Canada has made a contribution of $3 million from our fast-start climate financing to support the work of the Coalition.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="41">Canada has made a contribution of $3 million from our fast-start climate financing to support the work of the Coalition.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="41" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="0e6ef9c5-816d-438d-96d1-231cb3c6882c"><source>$473,000 of this contribution will go towards various HFC activities, including the development of an HFC inventory in 6-12 countries.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="42">$473,000 of this contribution will go towards various HFC activities, including the development of an HFC inventory in 6-12 countries.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="42" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="3c146a30-eda5-4959-8d26-d9a17920a5a6"><source>Domestic initiatives on HFCs</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="43">Domestic initiatives on HFCs</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="43" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="314d0827-170a-456b-ad68-ad156e751abf"><source>Although HFCs currently constitute only 1% of Canada’s GHG emissions, emissions are rising rapidly as HCFCs are phased-out.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="44">Although HFCs currently constitute only 1% of Canada’s GHG emissions, emissions are rising rapidly as HCFCs are phased-out.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="44" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="f80636c3-645b-4e9e-bca1-0ebdbf698796"><source>Domestic activities are already contributing to action on HFCs and emission reductions to some extent:</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="45">Domestic activities are already contributing to action on HFCs and emission reductions to some extent:</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="45" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="81780ddf-680d-464f-a093-332f4a5a4d94"><source>The wilful release of HFCs is prohibited, and provincial and federal regulations contain provisions to recover them from emitting systems;</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="46">The wilful release of HFCs is prohibited, and provincial and federal regulations contain provisions to recover them from emitting systems;</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="46" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="cd0ccf99-d658-4771-b3a6-68b36da9d36d"><source>Existing light duty vehicle regulations provide incentive for manufacturers to adopt alternatives for air conditioning systems, and thereby minimizing HFC emissions; and</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="47">Existing light duty vehicle regulations provide incentive for manufacturers to adopt alternatives for air conditioning systems, and thereby minimizing HFC emissions; and</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="47" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="270881ac-766d-40ab-9682-30ac3631e02a"><source>A mandatory survey is planned on HFC use, import and export to establish more accurate data in order to better assess the impacts of control options (Fall 2012).</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="48">A mandatory survey is planned on HFC use, import and export to establish more accurate data in order to better assess the impacts of control options (Fall 2012).</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="48" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="71789eef-d1d8-44df-b29a-7c75ab1a3a9a"><source>However, without comprehensively addressing the growing use of HFCs, these activities are unlikely to achieve sustainable and long-term HFC emission reductions.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="49">However, without comprehensively addressing the growing use of HFCs, these activities are unlikely to achieve sustainable and long-term HFC emission reductions.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="49" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="7537ebf2-ac1c-40c2-a222-f42d0fc86e50"><source><g id="pt56">A Strategic Approach to HFCs:</g>
Opportunities for scaled-up and coordinated action to achieve results</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="50"><g id="pt56">A Strategic Approach to HFCs:</g>
Opportunities for scaled-up and coordinated action to achieve results</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="50" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="595e38dd-3edc-4da5-a327-323a96e1435a"><source>Although Canada is already engaging on HFCs in various fora, this work has often been undertaken in an ad hoc manner and there is no comprehensive domestic plan to address the anticipated growth in HFC use and emissions.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="51">Although Canada is already engaging on HFCs in various fora, this work has often been undertaken in an ad hoc manner and there is no comprehensive domestic plan to address the anticipated growth in HFC use and emissions.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="51" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="d307dfe2-37ae-4088-856a-d8ac7d58c8c6"><source>A more strategic and coordinated approach would allow Canada to ensure coherence and synergy amongst ongoing and planned HFC activities, while pursuing scaled-up action on HFCs.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="52">A more strategic and coordinated approach would allow Canada to ensure coherence and synergy amongst ongoing and planned HFC activities, while pursuing scaled-up action on HFCs.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="52" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="99c20a68-914e-424d-83a6-ce317c80aaa9"><source>In particular, a strategic approach to HFCs would achieve the following key objectives:</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="53">In particular, a strategic approach to HFCs would achieve the following key objectives:</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="53" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="9fc1523a-fac1-411e-8707-4ed502b940aa"><source>Ensure coherence and synergy amongst ongoing, planned, and enhanced HFC activities;</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="54">Ensure coherence and synergy amongst ongoing, planned, and enhanced HFC activities;</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="54" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="76622849-d478-4346-b7bf-d0028969a6af"><source>Deliver climate benefits and possibly contribute to the achievement of Canada’s 2020 GHG reduction target;</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="55">Deliver climate benefits and possibly contribute to the achievement of Canada’s 2020 GHG reduction target;</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="55" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="518b1ed0-2dab-4f5d-95ba-cf0cfdabdcb6"><source>Contribute to enhanced cooperation with the U.S. and Mexico on climate change;</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="56">Contribute to enhanced cooperation with the U.S. and Mexico on climate change;</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="56" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="d7cd8e0e-bdf1-4dff-b7c9-158ad65c1100"><source>Reinforce our interest and leadership in addressing short-lived climate pollutants; and</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="57">Reinforce our interest and leadership in addressing short-lived climate pollutants; and</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="57" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="cd1f051d-b88e-4429-8ab5-ccd57b03aa73"><source>Ensure that financial implications of this work are understood and addressed in a coordinated manner.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="58">Ensure that financial implications of this work are understood and addressed in a coordinated manner.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="58" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="05d23049-a7d2-4c7f-961d-1a1de7f09005"><source>Enhanced Canadian action on HFCs: Proposed Strategic Approach and Objective</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="59">Enhanced Canadian action on HFCs: Proposed Strategic Approach and Objective</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="59" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="2a36a993-e7d5-4697-8727-665833b81ad6"><source>The overall <g id="pt63">objective </g>of this strategic approach is to <g id="pt64">promote cost effective domestic and international action to facilitate global control of HFCs, in particular actions that can build support for a phase-down of HFC consumption and production under the Montreal Protocol.</g></source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="60">The overall <g id="pt63">objective </g>of this strategic approach is to <g id="pt64">promote cost effective domestic and international action to facilitate global control of HFCs, in particular actions that can build support for a phase-down of HFC consumption and production under the Montreal Protocol.</g></mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="60" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="7066a9d1-d57c-4196-a744-c64196c74125"><source>Through a <g id="pt65">strategic approach on HFCs</g>, Canada will:</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="61">Through a <g id="pt65">strategic approach on HFCs</g>, Canada will:</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="61" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="ed46e487-001c-4653-ae7a-b6b1bc522470"><source>Continue to partner with the US and Mexico to promote a phase-down of HFCs under the Montreal Protocol; and</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="62">Continue to partner with the US and Mexico to promote a phase-down of HFCs under the Montreal Protocol; and</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="62" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="2fb4eaa5-a076-4faf-a369-c81692f621fa"><source>Pursue enhanced and coordinated action under the CCAC, UNFCCC and domestically, as appropriate, to support and lay the groundwork for a phase-down.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="63">Pursue enhanced and coordinated action under the CCAC, UNFCCC and domestically, as appropriate, to support and lay the groundwork for a phase-down.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="63" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="e29dcb8f-43e4-4407-bbb7-9691c5d3612d"><source>A Strategic Approach: Enhanced and coordinated international action on HFCs</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="64">A Strategic Approach: Enhanced and coordinated international action on HFCs</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="64" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="71861e9e-8053-4ebc-822d-843cfc939eaf"><source>Montreal Protocol</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="65">Montreal Protocol</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="65" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="f6a0a345-b14e-441a-b16c-4fdc662b1c74"><source>Continue to promote the NA Proposal and enhance advocacy efforts to build support;</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="66">Continue to promote the NA Proposal and enhance advocacy efforts to build support;</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="66" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="86735153-fe27-43a0-8cbe-c1b0da388e0b"><source>Promote the use of non-HFC alternatives to HCFC phase-out projects under the Protocol’s Multilateral Fund; and</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="67">Promote the use of non-HFC alternatives to HCFC phase-out projects under the Protocol’s Multilateral Fund; and</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="67" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="613fb14d-c4a7-4d83-a1f6-fa9deebeaa3a"><source>Encourage and participate in discussions on HFC alternatives through research initiatives and technology workshops.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="68">Encourage and participate in discussions on HFC alternatives through research initiatives and technology workshops.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="68" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="f0e64e16-1538-4d45-98d3-9588dbab3441"><source>CCAC</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="69">CCAC</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="69" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="250e960f-6b93-4bcd-8cd1-fa0d5c1c8ee0"><source>Identify and promote new activities that help to generate information on HFCs and avoid global use/emissions, focusing in particular on activities that are consistent with and support the NA Proposal; and</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="70">Identify and promote new activities that help to generate information on HFCs and avoid global use/emissions, focusing in particular on activities that are consistent with and support the NA Proposal; and</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="70" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="e843a518-53b5-48a4-aeaf-3a3cbc94d9ec"><source>Play an active role in implementing HFC-related initiatives and consider making further financial contributions to specific HFC activities.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="71">Play an active role in implementing HFC-related initiatives and consider making further financial contributions to specific HFC activities.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="71" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="ed1dcf61-196d-422a-82b3-f7a4e18c5462"><source>UNFCCC</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="72">UNFCCC</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="72" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="82dc194e-080d-424f-9aa0-ee3364e01cdd"><source>As appropriate, support and raise awareness of NA Proposal under the UNFCCC;</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="73">As appropriate, support and raise awareness of NA Proposal under the UNFCCC;</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="73" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="bc73403b-9899-4e08-99c2-964ca2b5feb1"><source>Discuss HFCs and the NA Proposal through the Durban Platform; and</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="74">Discuss HFCs and the NA Proposal through the Durban Platform; and</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="74" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="581c58c1-0f19-4227-9f85-3046bdcde7d4"><source>Work to ensure perverse incentives are not created for HFC production and consumption through the CDM or other mechanisms.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="75">Work to ensure perverse incentives are not created for HFC production and consumption through the CDM or other mechanisms.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="75" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="25f119fa-a5a8-4148-bf9b-76f2211c5b94"><source>A Strategic Approach: Enhanced domestic action</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="76">A Strategic Approach: Enhanced domestic action</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="76" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="993e02ed-dd71-480c-978b-ac24576bedf1"><source><g id="pt73">A Licensing and Reporting System for </g><g id="pt74">HFCs: 2014</g></source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="77"><g id="pt73">A Licensing and Reporting System for </g><g id="pt74">HFCs: 2014</g></mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="77" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="b71dffdd-7568-4c05-9e61-9e9c19d31a23"><source>EC could lay the groundwork domestically for an eventual phase-down of HFCs by amending existing ozone-depleting substances (ODS) regulations to include new HFC provisions to require a permit for HFC production, import and export;</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="78">EC could lay the groundwork domestically for an eventual phase-down of HFCs by amending existing ozone-depleting substances (ODS) regulations to include new HFC provisions to require a permit for HFC production, import and export;</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="78" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="436b792f-630d-4c98-b7a7-8219f8bd440a"><source>Should a global phase-down of HFC consumption and production be eventually agreed, EC could then gradually reduce allocations under the licensing system, in the same manner that it has done to phase out ODS</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="79">Should a global phase-down of HFC consumption and production be eventually agreed, EC could then gradually reduce allocations under the licensing system, in the same manner that it has done to phase out ODS</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="79" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="2f3ee75b-4f3d-4744-9a67-cb6f2c4a8fc2"><source>This would also contribute to addressing data gaps with respect to HFCs and combating illicit importation of ODS by ensuring that all refrigerants are subject to permitting requirements.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="80">This would also contribute to addressing data gaps with respect to HFCs and combating illicit importation of ODS by ensuring that all refrigerants are subject to permitting requirements.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="80" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="34d56b15-dae3-424b-835e-7d738efb75ce"><source>Industry is generally supportive of these measures and, in some cases, requested them.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="81">Industry is generally supportive of these measures and, in some cases, requested them.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="81" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="bd161718-2377-4e0d-8da8-41207bfb1d25"><source>Environment Canada should also…</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="82">Environment Canada should also…</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="82" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="abddc5af-e8da-4ed9-9fb8-3a8add018613"><source>Collaborate with US EPA officials regarding the possibility of restricting certain HFC uses;</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="83">Collaborate with US EPA officials regarding the possibility of restricting certain HFC uses;</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="83" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="caf3270e-ff65-4839-9928-b0342fe0fe57"><source>Promote HFC alternatives through existing government-industry working groups; and</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="84">Promote HFC alternatives through existing government-industry working groups; and</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="84" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="8b45dbcb-27eb-41c5-9317-4527965f1dab"><source>Refine HFC use and emission projections by using HFC data acquired through mandatory surveys and regulations</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="85">Refine HFC use and emission projections by using HFC data acquired through mandatory surveys and regulations</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="85" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="554b2329-05e0-4720-9e8c-3960c65514c1"><source>A Strategic Approach: Continue to advance the North American Proposal</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="86">A Strategic Approach: Continue to advance the North American Proposal</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="86" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="2edcf27f-a794-453c-a36e-9f5748bbf375"><source>The core component of this strategic approach is to continue to advance the North American Proposal under the Montreal Protocol.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="87">The core component of this strategic approach is to continue to advance the North American Proposal under the Montreal Protocol.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="87" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="5ef7faad-68ff-41d8-8ff1-0b1f4dee1a83"><source>Although certain countries (Brazil, China, India) oppose the North American Proposal, support continues to build every year that it is introduced.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="88">Although certain countries (Brazil, China, India) oppose the North American Proposal, support continues to build every year that it is introduced.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="88" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="38c970fa-d170-41c5-ac38-e4962b1d5d25"><source>Australia, the EU, and many developing countries are on board.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="89">Australia, the EU, and many developing countries are on board.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="89" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="73654c52-b63d-4d30-afc4-2b56ecbc2e42"><source>If adopted, a global HFC phase-down under the Montreal Protocol could potentially result in domestic GHG reductions of 5.6 MT of CO<g id="pt80">2</g><g id="pt81"> </g>e in 2020, and a cumulative reduction of 524.7 MT CO<g id="pt82">2</g><g id="pt83"> </g>e by 2050.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="90">If adopted, a global HFC phase-down under the Montreal Protocol could potentially result in domestic GHG reductions of 5.6 MT of CO<g id="pt80">2</g><g id="pt81"> </g>e in 2020, and a cumulative reduction of 524.7 MT CO<g id="pt82">2</g><g id="pt83"> </g>e by 2050.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="90" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="9f48b057-bb00-4a2d-a6f7-7b345b4d200f"><source>This could be an important contribution to Canada’s future emissions reductions</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="91">This could be an important contribution to Canada’s future emissions reductions</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="91" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="b5d4467f-41ce-4fd5-b8bd-61e135cf7a7e"><source>Globally, a phase-down of HFCs under the Montreal Protocol would result in significant global climate benefits, with potential emission reductions of 96,300 MT <g id="pt85">CO</g><g id="pt86">2</g><g id="pt87"> </g><g id="pt88">e </g><g id="pt89">from 2016 to 2050.</g></source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="92">Globally, a phase-down of HFCs under the Montreal Protocol would result in significant global climate benefits, with potential emission reductions of 96,300 MT <g id="pt85">CO</g><g id="pt86">2</g><g id="pt87"> </g><g id="pt88">e </g><g id="pt89">from 2016 to 2050.</g></mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="92" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="b6056d88-3963-4bfc-8b5e-114da666c4d7"><source>A Strategic Approach: Continue to advance the North American Proposal (2)</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="93">A Strategic Approach: Continue to advance the North American Proposal (2)</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="93" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="964345a5-48d7-4b7d-b5f2-a302aa89bf64"><source>A successful North American Proposal would entail various implications for Canada, and it is important these implications are fully appreciated.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="94">A successful North American Proposal would entail various implications for Canada, and it is important these implications are fully appreciated.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="94" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
