<trans-unit id="d1ecf5e0-a86e-4cd5-bbd7-ee4a70ff0cf2"><source>An HFC phase-down under the Montreal Protocol would require developed countries to provide increased contributions to the Multilateral Fund (MLF).</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="96">An HFC phase-down under the Montreal Protocol would require developed countries to provide increased contributions to the Multilateral Fund (MLF).</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="96" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="068f411e-a802-44b3-94db-41bec423fd79"><source>An HFC phase-down would require an increase in replenishment of the MLF by as much as 25% starting in 2015, and 50% from 2018-2035.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="97">An HFC phase-down would require an increase in replenishment of the MLF by as much as 25% starting in 2015, and 50% from 2018-2035.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="97" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="988fafb7-0ba9-4266-9b69-4eb8f8c188e7"><source><g id="pt94">Estimated costs </g><g id="pt95">for Canada would amount to </g><g id="pt96">approximately $2.7 million USD per year from 2018-2035, above Canada’s current annual contribution of $5.4 million (based on Canada’s current share of 4.1%).</g></source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="98"><g id="pt94">Estimated costs </g><g id="pt95">for Canada would amount to </g><g id="pt96">approximately $2.7 million USD per year from 2018-2035, above Canada’s current annual contribution of $5.4 million (based on Canada’s current share of 4.1%).</g></mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="98" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="fd57068e-4c71-4eb1-b26c-9b7c05b53950"><source><g id="pt97">Global costs are expected to be around $2.5 billion for the period 2015-2045, amounting to a cost of less than 50 cents per tonne CO</g><g id="pt98">2</g><g id="pt99">e – one of the most cost effective ways to reduce GHGs in developing countries.</g></source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="99"><g id="pt97">Global costs are expected to be around $2.5 billion for the period 2015-2045, amounting to a cost of less than 50 cents per tonne CO</g><g id="pt98">2</g><g id="pt99">e – one of the most cost effective ways to reduce GHGs in developing countries.</g></mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="99" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
<trans-unit id="44567dd9-8ed9-4891-9c28-dcf41ea7b050"><source>No source of funds has been identified but this could be part of an MC ask on HFCs specifically, and/or be part of Canada’s long-term climate finance commitment.</source><seg-source><mrk mtype="seg" mid="100">No source of funds has been identified but this could be part of an MC ask on HFCs specifically, and/or be part of Canada’s long-term climate finance commitment.</mrk></seg-source><sdl:seg-defs><sdl:seg id="100" /></sdl:seg-defs></trans-unit>
